            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe remembers the precise weight of the stamped metal keys in his palm. It was 2008. After months of navigating shelters and paperwork, he handed them to a 17-year-old kid named Marcus, who had been sleeping in a bus tunnel. Marcus didn't cheer; he just stared at the keys, a single tear tracing a path through the grime on his cheek. In that silent moment, Joshua felt the crushing weight of the city's failure lift, replaced by a fierce, protective conviction. It was the first time he truly believed his work could matter.\n\n2.\nOne night around 2015, after learning a client he\u2019d spent a year with had fatally overdosed, he sat on the curb of a loud Mission street. The smell of fried carnitas mixed with diesel fumes and hopelessness. He thought of his father leaving the steel mill, exhausted and coated in grit. He\u2019d come to San Francisco to escape that kind of systemic despair, only to find it in a different form. It was a profound, hollowed-out feeling that almost broke him, forging a permanent, cynical edge to his compassion.\n\n3.\nHe came home one evening, around age 32, so emotionally decimated he couldn\u2019t form words. Clara didn\u2019t press him. She simply put on an old black-and-white film, made two cups of tea, and sat beside him on the sofa. As the steam from his mug warmed his hands and the movie\u2019s score filled the quiet apartment, he felt a profound sense of safety. He learned then that love wasn\u2019t about fixing problems, but about creating a space where the broken pieces could safely rest for a while.\n\n4.\nRiding through Golden Gate Park on a Tuesday morning last spring, he felt a moment of perfect clarity. The fog was burning off the tops of the eucalyptus trees, which looked like ancient green cathedrals. For ten minutes, there were no case files, no intractable problems, just the rhythmic whir of his bike chain and the damp, earthy smell of the park. This daily ritual wasn't an escape; it was his armor. It was the moment he gathered the peace he would need to face the day\u2019s inevitable heartbreak.\n\n5.\nAt the clinic\u2019s holiday party two years ago, a woman he\u2019d helped into a housing program in 2012 introduced him to her daughter. The little girl, shyly holding her mother\u2019s leg, gave him a small wave. Seeing that family\u2014stable, together, a direct result of connections forged years prior\u2014crystallized his purpose. It wasn't about singular victories anymore. It was about building a web of support strong enough to last, planting the seed for his dream of creating a real mentorship program within the clinic walls."
